Title : Ramayana Ballet
Text : {{Dance drama of Southeast Asia
|image   = [[File:Ramayana Java.jpg|200px]]
|caption = Javanese Ramayana Ballet in [[Prambanan]] temple
}}
The '''Ramayana Ballet''' ({{lang-id|'''Sendratari Ramayana'''}}) is a visualization and representation of the epic ''[[Ramayana]]'' saga, originally written by [[Valmiki]] in the [[Sanskrit]] language, in a highly stylized dance artform. Ramayana Ballet performance combines music, [[dance]] and [[drama]], usually performed without dialogue.<ref name="ministry"> {{cite web|title= Long running Prambanan Ramayana Ballet wins PATA Gold Award 2012|publisher= Ministry of Tourism and Creative Economy, Republic of Indonesia|accessdate= 3 May 2014|url= http://www.indonesia.travel/en/news/detail/701/long-running-prambanan-ramayana-ballet-wins-pata-gold-award-2012|deadurl= yes|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140503121536/http://www.indonesia.travel/en/news/detail/701/long-running-prambanan-ramayana-ballet-wins-pata-gold-award-2012|archivedate= 3 May 2014|df= }}</ref> 

Originated in [[India]], Ramayana has become a fertile source of artistic inspirations, especially in Southeast Asian nations that historically was heavily influenced by [[Indianised kingdoms|dharmic civilization]]. Ramayana ballet or dance drama can be found in several traditions in Asia, namely as ''Sendratari Ramayana'' in [[Indonesia]] (Java and Bali), ''[[Ramakien]]'' dance in [[Dance in Thailand|Thailand]], and ''[[Reamker]]'' dance in [[Dance in Cambodia|Cambodia]].

==Indonesia==
[[File:Ramayana Bali Ubud 1.jpg|thumb|280px|left|Balinese Ramayana dance drama, performed in Sarasvati Garden in [[Ubud]].]]
In [[Dance in Indonesia|Indonesia]], Ramayana mainly can be found in two major dance traditions; the [[Javanese dance|Javanese]] and [[Balinese dance|Balinese traditions]], presented as a complete set of performing art including dance drama and intricate [[gamelan]] orchestra. 

In Java, Ramayana ballet is part of Javanese [[Wayang Wong]] tradition, as the performance combines traditional [[Javanese dance|Javanese]] dance, drama, and [[music]].<ref name="ministry"/> In Java, Indonesia, Ramayana ballet regularly performed in many places, such as: at the Hindu temple [[Prambanan]], also known as [[Prambanan Ramayana Ballet]]; Purawisata Ramayana Ballet, at [[Yogyakarta]] Purawisata cultural center; and Hyatt Regency Yogyakarta Hotel.<ref name="jak">{{cite web|title= ‘Ramayana’ ballet breaks world records|publisher= Jakarta Post|accessdate= 3 May 2014|url= http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/10/17/ramayana-ballet-breaks-world-records.html}}</ref><ref name="jog">{{cite web|url= http://www.tourjogja.com/jogjaevents-7-ramayana-ballet-at-purawisata-jogja.html|title= Ramayana Ballet at Purawisata Jogja|accessdate= 15 May 2014|publisher=Tourjogja.com}}</ref><ref name="hyatt">{{cite web|url=http://yogyakarta.regency.hyatt.com/en/hotel/activities/area-activities/ramayanaballetperformance.html|publisher= Hyatt Hotel|accessdate= 15 May 2014|title= Ramayana Ballet Performance}}</ref>

In [[Bali]], Ramayana ballet is performed in two forms, as stylized ''sendratari'' (lit. ballet) as those performed in [[Ubud]], or as part of [[Kecak]] dance as those performed in [[Pura Luhur Uluwatu|Uluwatu temple]].

